title: Safety Advisor
name: Richard Joa
description: This position interacts with clients(s) and personnel and is responsible for the supervision, coordination, and administration of safety of project sites(s). Maintain knowledge of applicable rules and regulations including relative government regulations, standards and policies. Carry out inspections and audits of the workplace and conduct stop work instruction for any imminent danger situations that may be encountered. Promote toolbox meetings, and safety awareness. Provide direction and support in the investigation of all safety incidents. Administer safety policies and ensure the site and the employees adhere to the relevant occupational health and safety legislation. Ensure that all employees’ work in a safe manner. Maintain safety documentation and provide the necessary reports required for daily and weekly HSE related activities and statistics. Assists in the development of job safety plans. Complete WCB forms as required Assist in responding to RFQ’s from clients. Conduct risk assessments Advising the Safety Committee (as applicable) Complete IRATA Level 1 training Travel to other Acuren offices and projects situated out of town sites to support other Safety Team members and work based on need and scope of work.

title: Senior Watch Officer Regional Joint Operations Center
name: Richard Joa
description: Regional Joint Operations Centre (RJOC), Senior Watch Officer (SWO) The Senior Watch Officer (SWO) supervises and is responsible for the conduct of all facets of the watch and the unit mission during the period of the watch. The SWO is responsible to the RJOC Atlantic Director for the conduct of the watch and to Day Support Staff for matters relating to appropriate operational procedures. In addition to those duties detailed in Standard Operating Proceedures (SOPs), the SWO shall: a. act as MARLANT Commander's Officer of the Watch and assume all the duties and responsibilities inherent in that position; b. task surveillance sources and sensors as required including the activation of allied support on behalf of MARLANT units; c. combine multiple source surveillance information in order to build and maintain an operation/tactical level surveillance picture of all surface activity in CANLANT; d. advise appropriate operations staff of any unusual activity in the MARLANT AOR; e. provide 24/7, all source, Indications and Warnings support to command authorities and deployed forces, as required; f. maintain an operational/ strategic picture of activity in any areas abroad where MARLANT forces are operating; g. be aware of movements of any senior officers; h. recall, as required, for all operational and administrative incidents and inform MARLANT N3, his designated representative or the Commander of MARLANT directly of the situation and/or his/her actions; i. liaise with the JRCC Halifax for coordination of forces as required in emergencies; j. ensure the operations brief is prepared and ready for presentation to the Commanding Officer; k. maintain a training program that does not conflict with the mission, and when time is available, permits personnel to work on qualifications; l. read all incoming message traffic (with the exception of CO exclusive messages), and take appropriate action as dictated by the message priority

title: Information Management Director
name: Richard Joa
description: Information Management Director Officer (IMDO) The IMDO is the Divisional Officer for the Combat Information Division (CIO) which is responsible to the Combat Officer for: a. act as ship’s Intelligence Officer which includes; coordinating the requirement for intelligence; including electronic intelligence and signals intelligence (ELINT/SIGINT), collecting, collating and disseminating intelligence; ensuring daily intelligence briefings for the Commanding Officer are prepared at sea; obtaining adequate intelligence training aids; supervising a ship-wide recognition awareness program; attending intelligence briefings in harbour; being prepared to brief the Commanding Officer; complement the development and vision of shipboard IM/IS by participating as the secretary of the ships Information Management Committee; b. provide operational input to the information management (IM) committee and assist in the development of a shipboard IM Plan; c. act as the secretary to the ships Information Requirements Committee; d. ideally, act as the ship’s Confidential Standards Documents (CSD) custodian; e. coordinate operational input to classified web sites.

title: Naval Officer
name: Richard Joa
description: Navy Lieutenant (Army/Air Force Captain equivalent) The primary function of Maritime Surface and Sub-Surface (MARS) officers is to be a part of the crew of the seagoing combatant units of Maritime Command. They are responsible for the command, coordination and control of Military Maritime Operations that require the ability to lead and make decisions, often under adverse conditions. They must possess knowledge and expertise in a wide range of activities relating to the exercise of sea power, including maritime strategy, tactics and procedures in the operation of ships, submarines and aircraft, maritime sensors, combat information and weapons systems. MARS officers also provide input into the design, procurement and evaluation of ships or systems and perform staff, training and administrative duties.

title: Officer of the Watch
name: Richard Joa
description: Officer of the Watch The Officer of the Watch (OOW) exercises Command over the entire Ships Company, with the exception of the CO and XO. He or she is responsible for the proper of and safe movement of the ship and her company while at Sea. While standing watch the OOW shall: a. Keep continually informed concerning the tactical situation and geographic factors that may affect safe navigation of the ship, and take appropriate action to avoid the danger of grounding or collision according to tactical doctrine, the Collision Regulations, and the orders of the CO; b. Keep informed concerning of current operation plans and orders, intentions of the Officer in Tactical Command (OTC) and the CO, and such other matters as may pertain to ship or force operations; c. Issue necessary orders to the helm and main engine control to avoid danger, to take or keep an assigned station, or to change the course and speed of the ship according to orders of proper authority; d. Make all required reports to the CO; e. Ensure that required reports to the OOW concerning tests and inspections and the routine reports of patrols are promptly originated and that the bridge watch and lookouts are properly posted and alert; f. Ensure that the XO and department heads concerned are kept informed of changes in the tactical situation, operation schedule, the approach of heavy weather, and other circumstances that would require a change in the ships routine or other action on their part; g. Keep informed of the status and current capabilities of the engineering plant and keep the Engineering Officer of the Watch (EOOW) advised concerning power requirements and the operational situation so they may operate the engineering plant intelligently; h. Carry out the routine of the ship as published in Ships Standing Orders (SSO’s), keeping the XO advised of any changes that may be necessary;

title: Diver and Dive Officer
name: Richard Joa
description: Dive Officer and Diver, (DIVEO) The DIVEO is responsible to the Executive Officer (XO) for: a. Developing, coordinating and administering CF diving policy as well as safety policies and practices; b. managing CF diving publications; c. approving CF diving procedures and use of equipment; d. promulgating CF diving policy through DAOD 8009-0, Canadian Forces Diving; e. promulgating CF diving orders and further instructions through the Diving Manual; f. enforcing CF diving orders and instructions; g. representing CF diving with respect to national and international diving policies and regulations; h. investigating and closing all serious diving incident and accident investigations from the perspective of safety policy; j. and chairing the Canadian Forces Diving Policy Committee (CFDPC).

title: Op Hestia
name: Richard Joa
description: Operation Hestia, Haiti Joint Task Force Haiti (JTFH) was a humanitarian operations task force with a mandate to deliver a wide range of services in support of the Government of Haiti and the Canadian Embassy in Port-au-Prince in particular, JTFH offered emergency medical services; engineering expertise; mobility by sea, land and air; and Defence and security support. At peak, the maritime, land and air components of JTFH comprised about 2,050 personnel divided between Port-au-Prince, Léogâne and Jacmel. JTFH was responsible for: a. construction of a beachheads and medical triage centers; b. clearance of rubble and debris; c. construction of latrines and water distribution points at orphanages and camps for internally displaced people; d. removal of trees from the airfield to allowing CC-130 Hercules aircraft to land; e. crowd control at humanitarian aid distribution points and maintenance of complex equipment, including Reverse Osmosis Water Purification Units.
